for this study?"
I consent to being interviewed and audio recorded for this interview.
Okay, to get started, can you tell me about how you came to live in this community?

Okay, so I was born at the [LOCAL HOSPITAL] um on Christmas Day, um and I am the youngest of

Hmm. I would probably describe [LOCAL COMMUNITY] as a very family um oriented place. Um, I feel

had experiences with I feel like there's a mix of-a diversity in [LOCAL COMMUNITY], maybe not as

It's a good question. Um, I think that um I don't know, like, I think I can describe [LOCAL COMMUNITY]
better from because when you grow up living somewhere, you sort of accept everything about it. And

Well, [LAUGHS] yeah, friendliness and um and I think um I, I really like the I-I think that that in every

For um
As a teacher.
As a teacher?

Yes.
But a typical school day.

What do you think that means?

Well, um I think it means to, that it's not it, to me, it's kind of a mission, it's not just a job, right? Because

Yeah, um what aspects of your job when you were a teacher brought you the most joy or satisfaction?
[SPEAKING IN THE BACKGROUND]

Hmm. I had a-I had a teacher that I was able to kind of learn from and my student teaching. And one of
the things that she taught me was um parents don't-nobody wants to hear negative. If they've never
heard a positive from you, they'll-they'll never accept a negative. So she taught me how to encourage.
And like um I would call parents. So I make calls every single day. And I chose three parents to call.
And I would tell them something good. And so in order to make that um, like, actually look like an
legitimate thing where they're not kind of questioning why is she calling and saying this cheesy thing. I
would just sort of watch the classroom. And then I would pick a kid out of that, like, if a something good

helped me to be more thankful about my day just because you can sometimes there's days where
you're just like, the class was awful and this and you can get negative, you know, but when I was

Yeah. I love that.
Mhm.

Okay. I've lived in Texas all my life. I was born in Titus County. And when I was five, we moved a-to a
farm near White House, which is south east of Tyler. I liked growing up in the country and when my
chores were done I'd ride my horse, climb trees or hike down to the creek to fish or swim. One time we
tied a rope to a limb of a cypress tree, and we'd swing out wide over the swimming hole and drop into
the water. I'd pretend to be Tarzan swinging on a vine. In the spring I'd fly kites, and on summer nights
we'd catch fireflies, but we called them lightning bugs. Once in a while we'd have bites with corn cobs
or pine cones. And in the winter, we build a fire in the fireplace and pop popcorn and roast peanuts and
pecans. I guess I was a Livewire. When I was 19 I went to work in Dallas at a Firestone Tire store. I
didn't like city life, and for a long time I'd go home every chance I got. Mama would always cook my
favorite foods fried okra, hoppin john, that's-that's rice and black-black eyed peas and pecan pie. We
had lots of good times, but going home is not the same now. After daddy died, mama tol-sold the farm
and moved to Tyler. I'd rather be living on a farm right now instead of here in the city. My wife and my
kids don't understand me when I gripe about city life and talk about moving to a country. I'm sorry to the
country. My oldest child says "Daddy, that's crazy. I'd just die if I had to live on a farm." I almost cried
the first time she said that. I know Texas is changing, but I try to make sure we don't lose touch with our
roots. While we may live in a city, I want my kids to have a good feeling for the land. Have a sense of
place and take pride in being Texans. If they lose our-if they lose our ties to the land, the price of
progress is too high.
